Title: Re: What music are you listening to right now?
Post by: Inorganik on August 25, 2012, 05:20 pm
Kristoff Krane - Leave the Summer (Brighter Side by Kristoff Krane is also a good one).
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bZo6ihtN3tc

^ Is what I'm listening to at the moment. While I'm at it, I suppose I will link some of the other music I like :).

1. http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_jzj87z-Mjk (Sacred Frequencies by Machine drum)
"‘Sacred Frequency’ opens the EP with floods of spiralling synth washes and organ chords over kicks and snares, before ushering in Travis' sweet psychedelic vocals. It’s an unexpectedly catchy and poppy track, and it’s not much of a stretch to call it one of the freshest pop moments this year." - Taken from Planet Mu Records.

2. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gAg3uMlNyHA (Wings by Macklemore)
Just a really great song by a really great artist. Seattle Hip-Hop.

3. www.youtube.com/watch?v=5mOIXdC4rgA (Anti War Dub by Digital Mystikz)
I dunno if you guys are into South London dubstep, but for me it puts me into a really chill mood. I like the UK Garage / 2step scene, but I am also into more popular dubstep artists (or brostep if you're a genre nazi :P) such a Zeds Dead. If you like this, check out Skream, Distance, as well as Vex'd.

4. www.youtube.com/watch?v=M2vVbYjdAjg (Drum n Baasa by Infected Mushroom)
This is a psychedelic trance duo from Israel. This particular song is part of their new album "Army of Mushrooms", which I really like. They are starting to get a lot more fame by joining the dubstep scene, which I'm not too proud of. But still, I like their more underground stuff :).

5. www.youtube.com/watch?v=y9MpwzM13MI (River Runs Deep by KnowMads)
A friend of mine actually introduced me to this artist. I am very glad she showed me the KnowMads, to say the least. They are Seattle Hip-Hop as well.

Title: Re: What music are you listening to right now?
Post by: 35mm on September 04, 2012, 03:22 am
I've been listening to a lot of Olafur Arnalds, Nils Fram, Johann Johannsson and Dustin O'Halloran.

Really good stuff if you like soft piano, strings and relaxing melodies. It's all contemporary classical music and its tone varies by artist and album.. Anything by them is a good start but I recommend Olafur Arnald's Living room songs to start.. and Johann Johannsson's Fordlandia if you have the patience to go through 10 minute tracks packed with strings and woodwinds.

You don't need to be a classical enthusiast to get into this!

Post by: Ballzinator on September 06, 2012, 02:54 am
I'm listening to some crazy shit I found on freemusicarchive.org.
http://freemusicarchive.org/music/SOUNDSHOCK/FM_FUNK_MADDNESS
The album is licensed under a Creative Commons license.

My favorite tunes from the album:
Dong - Mirror Maze
hex125 - pf (NRTDRV funk edit)
Simon Stålenhag - Ripple Boogie
Utabi Hirokawa - Stop and Go (Ubiktune edit)
Zabutom - Endorphemeral

The genre is called "Skweee". If I had to explain Skweee I'd call it funky chip-tune electronica. People who are interested in experimental music might like it.

Title: Re: What music are you listening to right now?
Post by: clandestination on January 22, 2013, 09:39 am
Quote from: bigdaddy5150 on December 18, 2012, 03:17 pm
Quote from: clandestination on December 17, 2012, 02:55 am
good kid, m.A.A.d. city - Kendrick Lamar - fucking ay!

His last two albums rocked my world. I was well into rap up until I guess Dr Dre brought along Xzibit and Eminem for their first few albums (still great artists, but not what i started listening to rap for) . Then everything (for somebody who is into music production, not genres) was not really to my liking.

Kendrick Fucking Lamar...your cd's are raping my car stereo.

All my hiphopheads need to listen to the El Jefe intro on It's Tha World... on repeat for 3 days now

If you like the production on Kendrick's album you should check out Game's. He has some seriously nasty beats on there. Not just throb-heavy club songs, but some seriously good hip-hop production. And a lot of people tried to compare Kdot to NaS, saying that gkmc was similar to Illmatic, so if you like lyricism then check out Life is Good by NaS. My favorite album this year, and that's including Curren$y, Big K.R.I.T, Game, Kendrick, Big Boi, and I would even go so far as to mention Freddie Gibbs' BFK mixtape along with those.

Electronic music just really doesn't do it for me. Don't ask me why, it's just not for me.

love Jeezy and smashing it, rest assured. Good tip to the rest of any folk into hiphop. I would +1 you if i didnt recycle accounts so often. haha.

Don't dig electronic music? Consider the fact that all rap / hiphop is made in the exact same way as electronic music. I would say 90% of it at least. A lot of m.A.A.d city has been sequenced with lots of synthesizers and tracked beats. just different tempo and sounds.

"You killed my cousin back in '94, Fuck your truce !" still raping my car stereo :) Filthy wigger I am...

"Although might pass-by both winter and spring,

and if you wait on high, I’ll meet you there, my friend".

Title: Re: What music are you listening to right now?
Post by: Fallkniven on February 01, 2013, 11:22 am
System of a Down - Soil

The song has very strong lyrics, powerful, meaningful, raw, abrupt, abrasive to the soul. I fucken love it, my fave System tune.

Some cool info about the song -

"Before System of a Down formed, Serj Tankian had his own band and so did Daron Malakian. They met in a recording studio and began playing together. They later picked up a drummer (Not John Dolmayan) and a Bassist. (Not Shavo Odadjian) They were called Soil. After a gig, the drummer and the bassist thought Soil was going nowhere, so they quit. Serj and Daron stayed together though. They later picked up Shavo as their Band Manager, then picked up a drummer, John Dolmayan. Shavo later became their bassist. They decided to name themselves System of a Down after Daron's poem entitled "Victims of the Down." They chose System because they believed it addressed a wider audience and because they also wanted to be closer (Alphabetically) to their current idol band "Slayer." After a year, System of a Down became substantially larger. At the same time, believed to be associated with his anger and frustration, Soil's previous bassist committed suicide via shooting himself in the head, hints the song's name, "Soil" and "Blew of his own mother f--king head." Also hints "Friends for years, images in red." System has been very quiet when it comes to the meaning of this song, although this is the most probable meaning of Soil, based on clues."

"
Don't you, realize, evil,
Lives in the motherfuckin skin,
Don't you, realize , that evil,
Lives in the motherfucking skin.
Why the fuck did you take him away from us you MOTHERFUCKEEEERRRRRR!!!!
"

A mood-mix of Internet stations via household wireless Sonos system:
SOMA FM Lush (US) commercial free, commercial free, self explanatory
SOMA FM Covers  (US) commercial free, self explanatory
Chilltrax (Origin Unknown) English language callsign commercial free trippy lounge
ABC Dig Music (Australia) commercial free mostly just awesome background stuff you won't hear anywhere else -tagline 'All the music you never knew you needed'.
ABC Triple J (Australia) commercial free  -if you are in college this station is for you, phenomenal for decades
Candlelight Radio (Netherlands) Dutch callsign commercial free for 1970-80-90's top 100 nostalgia romantic edge.
Radio Caroline (former venerable pirate station out of EU) but with English DJs and a hard rock edge.

Yes, this is a good one, but I don't have it. We're starting to move into 'Can't get' territory here people -- 5 backwards are going to be A) second-hand, B) expensive. I challenge you to find them A) brand new, B) not expensive. Remember BC's (yeah, Ice-T, the black guy from Law and Order SVU named Fin, wife has a well-documented ass) delightful Cop Killer? Banned same month. Now? Oh -- forget it. You won't get one, even second-hand..... price went up soon as banned and that was a while ago. Now? No one is stupid enough to sell. Older MOS CDs are more expensive than brand new MOS releases. The theory went something like this..... 1 CD = $30, dropping to $20 over time. 2 CD release? Charge for two. 3 CD release? Charge for tree. Marketing didn't get it (college on a budget?) so initially charged Raz this amount to buy a MOS 2 CD release. Well, people got fed up and started ripping them b/c anal sex gets tiring after a while every time you want to buy some tunes, so third finger and an internet connection became man's new best friend. Eventually they said, "wow, no one is buying our stuff," and lowered the price. Um, okay, there may be other factors involved, I never said there wasn't. i used to LOVE eminem when i was about 12-13. i even thought 8 mile was good and everything. now i listen to his old stuff and it actually disturbs me. the normalisation of domestic violence and homophobia, just sooo much hatred in his words. white america is still a tune though. and til i collapse, sing for the moment, without me.. ok i admit i dug out my eminem show cd now, clearly my fav album and not as fucked up lyrically. maybe he was just a complete cunt when he was young but so was i tbh maybe he can be forgiven...

People either love it or are completely disgusted by it. Hats off to him for having the balls to do it.

Seems like some lyrics were clearly due to drug and relationship frustrations too.

Title: Re: What music are you listening to right now?
Post by: PlanB on August 07, 2013, 01:54 pm
Public Service Broadcast

A duo band that play instrumentals and write all the music, but they use old public service broadcast's or announcements for the vocals for their tracks. My favorite tracks are Everest & Spitfire, check them out, the concept sounds bit stupid on paper but my god there amazing. You never would have guessed that old broadcasts from different era's of history would meld so perfectly with different written music!

Check em!

Regards
PlanB :)
